- Supporting evidence: 1) trace row_count peak at 22:47:00 UTC with ts-route-service as the most-downstream target and highest row_count; 2) metric breach on ts-route-service socket KPI within the incident window; 3) later small increases in trace latency for route-related traces; 4) logs show increased row_count/throughput but no error_count>0 or textual error_logs.
- Confidence and rationale: High confidence that ts-route-service is the root cause because it is the most downstream faulty service observed at the earliest anomaly time and its socket KPI breached thresholds; other services showed transient downstream or caller-side spikes but no evidence of being the last faulty downstream service.
- Recommended immediate actions:
  1) Throttle or shed excess traffic to ts-route-service if possible (rate-limit or apply circuit-breaker) to stop ongoing overload.
  2) Scale ts-route-service horizontally (add instances) or increase socket/connection capacity temporarily.
